<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} keywords={keywords} article>
	<Hero variant="interior" title="The Complete Guide to Preneed Insurance in North Carolina" subtitle="What NC families need to know about costs, laws, Medicaid rules, carriers, and choosing the right plan." />

	<div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12">
		<Breadcrumbs items={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'Learn', href: '/learn' }, { label: 'Preneed Insurance in NC' }]} />

		<!-- Key Takeaway Box -->
		<div class="bg-teal-50 border-l-4 border-teal-600 rounded-r-xl p-6 mb-12">
			<p class="font-heading font-bold text-charcoal-900 mb-2">Key Takeaway</p>
			<p class="text-charcoal-700 leading-relaxed">Preneed insurance in North Carolina lets you lock in today's funeral prices, document your exact wishes, and &mdash; if structured as an irrevocable trust &mdash; protect those funds from Medicaid spend-down requirements. It's one of the most practical financial planning tools available to NC families.</p>
		</div>

		<!-- Section 1: What Is Preneed Insurance? -->
		<section class="mb-16">
			<SectionHeading title="What Is Preneed Insurance?" accent />
			<div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					Preneed insurance is a specialized life insurance or trust-funded arrangement designed specifically to pay for your funeral and burial expenses. Unlike general life insurance &mdash; which pays a lump sum to your beneficiary for any purpose &mdash; preneed funds are earmarked exclusively for funeral costs and are typically paid directly to the funeral home you select. This means the money bypasses probate entirely and is available immediately when the need arises, without your family having to file claims, wait for estate settlement, or come out of pocket.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					When you set up a preneed plan, you are making two important decisions at once. First, you are setting aside the financial resources to cover your funeral. Second, you are documenting exactly what you want &mdash; the type of service (traditional burial, cremation, celebration of life), the casket or urn, the music, the flowers, the readings, even the clothing you want to wear. Every detail is recorded so that when the time comes, your family does not have to guess. They simply hand the preneed contract to the funeral home, and everything unfolds exactly as you planned.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					This matters more than most people realize. Funeral costs have risen approximately 40% over the last decade, and they continue to climb at a rate that outpaces general inflation. The NFDA’s 2023 survey reports a national median of $8,300 for a funeral with burial — but that figure excludes the burial vault, cemetery plot, opening and closing fees, and grave marker, which virtually every family needs. When all costs are counted, North Carolina families typically spend $16,000 to $20,000 or more on a traditional burial. Cremation with a full memorial service generally runs $7,500 to $8,500 at local funeral homes, while direct cremation — the simplest option with no formal service — starts around $4,000 to $4,500. Most families who purchase preneed insurance invest between $4,000 and $20,000, depending on the level of service they choose and whether they are planning for one person or a couple.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					Preneed insurance locks in today's prices. That means the funeral you plan today will cost your family nothing additional, even if prices rise 30% or 50% by the time the plan is needed. For families on fixed incomes, or for anyone who wants to ensure their loved ones are not burdened with an unexpected five-figure expense during the worst week of their lives, preneed insurance is one of the most straightforward and effective financial tools available.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Section 2: How Preneed Insurance Works in North Carolina -->
		<section class="mb-16">
			<SectionHeading title="How Preneed Insurance Works in North Carolina" accent />
			<div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					North Carolina has a well-established regulatory framework governing preneed funeral contracts. The relevant statutes are found in N.C.G.S. &sect; 90-210.60 through 90-210.73, which make up Article 13D of the North Carolina General Statutes. These laws define how preneed contracts must be structured, how funds must be held, and what rights consumers have when purchasing a preneed plan.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					The North Carolina Board of Funeral Service oversees all preneed licensing in the state. Any individual who sells preneed funeral contracts must be licensed by the Board as a preneed funeral director or preneed sales agent. Agents are required to carry a $50,000 surety bond &mdash; a financial guarantee that protects consumers if anything goes wrong with their preneed contract. The application fee for a preneed license is $150, and agents must meet continuing education requirements to maintain their license.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					One of the strongest consumer protections in North Carolina preneed law is <strong>100% contract transferability</strong>. If you purchase a preneed plan with one funeral home and later decide you want to use a different provider &mdash; whether because you moved, the funeral home changed ownership, or you simply changed your mind &mdash; you have the legal right to transfer your entire plan and all associated funds to another licensed funeral home. You are never locked in. This portability is a significant advantage over preneed arrangements in some other states where transferability is limited.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					Under NC law, all preneed funds must be either placed in a state-regulated trust account or backed by an insurance policy. This means a preneed seller cannot simply pocket your money &mdash; it must be protected through one of these two mechanisms. The role of the licensed preneed funeral director is to guide you through this process: helping you select the right type of plan, documenting your wishes in detail, ensuring the financial arrangement complies with state law, and coordinating with the funeral home that will ultimately carry out your plan.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					Working with a licensed preneed funeral director like Duane means you have a professional advocate who understands both the regulatory landscape and the practical realities of funeral planning. Duane is licensed in North Carolina and can serve families throughout the state. You can verify any agent's license status through the <a href="https://ncbfs.org" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NC Board of Funeral Service</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Section 3: How Much Does Preneed Insurance Cost in NC? -->
		<section class="mb-16">
			<SectionHeading title="How Much Does Preneed Insurance Cost in NC?" accent />

			<div class="bg-linen rounded-xl p-8 mb-6 border border-border-light">
				<p class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-charcoal-900 mb-2">
					All-in NC traditional burial: <span class="text-burgundy-600">$16,000–$20,000+</span>
				</p>
				<p class="text-charcoal-500">Preneed insurance locks in today's price &mdash; your family never pays the difference.</p>
			</div>

			<div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					The cost of a preneed plan depends on the type of service you choose and the level of detail you want to include. Here is what North Carolina families can expect based on current industry data:
				</p>

				<div class="overflow-x-auto">
					<table class="w-full border-collapse text-sm">
						<thead>
							<tr class="bg-linen">
								<th class="text-left p-4 font-heading font-bold text-charcoal-900 border-b border-border-light">Service Type</th>
								<th class="text-left p-4 font-heading font-bold text-charcoal-900 border-b border-border-light">Typical Cost Range (NC)</th>
								<th class="text-left p-4 font-heading font-bold text-charcoal-900 border-b border-border-light">What's Included</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">Traditional Burial (all-in)</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">$16,000–$20,000+</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Funeral home services, casket, burial vault, cemetery plot, opening/closing fees, grave marker, death certificates</td>
							</tr>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">Cremation with Service</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">$7,500–$8,500</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Memorial service, urn, transportation, cremation fee, funeral home services</td>
							</tr>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">Direct Cremation</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">$4,000–$4,500</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Cremation only, basic container, transportation, minimal funeral home involvement</td>
							</tr>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">NFDA Median (partial)</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">$8,300</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">NFDA 2023 figure — excludes vault, cemetery, marker, and cash advances</td>
							</tr>
						</tbody>
					</table>
				</div>

				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					The all-in figures above reflect the realistic total a family will pay, including cemetery plot, burial vault, grave marker, opening and closing fees, and funeral home professional services. The NFDA’s published median of $8,300 excludes these costs — which is why many families are surprised by the final bill. When planning a preneed policy, it’s important to fund it at a level that covers the full anticipated cost, not just the funeral home’s base fees.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					It is worth noting that the cremation rate in North Carolina currently runs between 48% and 60%, which is below the national average of 63.4%. This means a higher proportion of Carolina families still choose traditional burial, which tends to be more expensive. As cremation rates rise, the mix of funeral costs will shift &mdash; but the overall trend is still upward. Funeral costs have increased roughly 40% over the past decade, and there is no indication that trend will slow down.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					Most preneed plans offer flexible payment options. You can pay in a single lump sum, which often provides the best value, or spread payments over monthly, quarterly, or annual installments over 1, 5, or 10 years. The right payment schedule depends on your budget and your timeline. Duane will walk you through the options and help you find a plan that fits comfortably within your means. To discuss your specific situation, call <a href={`tel:${PHONE_RAW}`} class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">{PHONE}</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Section 4: Trust-Funded vs Insurance-Funded Preneed -->
		<section class="mb-16">
			<SectionHeading title="Trust-Funded vs Insurance-Funded Preneed in NC" accent />
			<div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					In North Carolina, preneed plans are funded through one of two mechanisms: a state-regulated trust account or a life insurance policy. While both are legally valid, insurance-funded preneed has become the overwhelming standard in current practice — the vast majority of NC funeral homes and preneed agents work exclusively with insurance-funded plans. Trust-funded preneed remains a legal option but is now relatively rare. Understanding the distinction is still useful, particularly for Medicaid planning purposes.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Trust-funded preneed</strong> means your payments are deposited into a trust account regulated by the state of North Carolina. The trustee &mdash; typically a bank or trust company &mdash; manages the funds, which grow through interest and investment earnings on a tax-deferred basis. North Carolina law allows trustees to retain up to 10% of trust fund earnings for administrative costs. When the plan is needed, the trust pays the funeral home directly. If the trust earnings exceed the cost of the funeral, the excess may be returned to your estate. Trust-funded preneed can be structured as either revocable (you can cancel and get your money back) or irrevocable (you give up access to the funds in exchange for Medicaid exemption).
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Insurance-funded preneed</strong> means your preneed plan is backed by a whole life insurance policy, with the funeral home named as the beneficiary. You pay premiums either in a lump sum or over a set period, and the policy grows in value over time on a tax-free basis. When you pass, the insurance company pays the death benefit directly to the funeral home. If the benefit exceeds the funeral costs, the excess typically goes to your estate or a named secondary beneficiary. Insurance-funded plans are more common today because they offer guaranteed growth, are not subject to market fluctuations, and provide full coverage even if you pass before all premiums are paid.
				</p>

				<div class="overflow-x-auto">
					<table class="w-full border-collapse text-sm">
						<thead>
							<tr class="bg-linen">
								<th class="text-left p-4 font-heading font-bold text-charcoal-900 border-b border-border-light">Feature</th>
								<th class="text-left p-4 font-heading font-bold text-charcoal-900 border-b border-border-light">Trust-Funded</th>
								<th class="text-left p-4 font-heading font-bold text-charcoal-900 border-b border-border-light">Insurance-Funded</th>
							</tr>
						</thead>
						<tbody>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">How funds grow</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Interest/investment earnings (tax-deferred)</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Guaranteed cash value growth (tax-free)</td>
							</tr>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">Full coverage if death occurs early</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Only amount deposited + earnings</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Full death benefit from day one</td>
							</tr>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">Medicaid exemption</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Yes, if irrevocable</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Yes, if irrevocable assignment</td>
							</tr>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">Administrative fees</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Up to 10% of earnings (NC law)</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Built into premium structure</td>
							</tr>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">Portability</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Transferable per NC law</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Transferable per NC law</td>
							</tr>
							<tr class="border-b border-border-light">
								<td class="p-4 font-semibold text-charcoal-900">Best for</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Medicaid planning, lump-sum deposits</td>
								<td class="p-4 text-charcoal-700">Most families, especially those paying over time</td>
							</tr>
						</tbody>
					</table>
				</div>

				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					For virtually all North Carolina families today, insurance-funded preneed is the standard — and the right choice. It provides full coverage from day one (for healthy applicants), offers predictable growth, and simplifies the claims process. Trust-funded preneed remains a legal option but is rarely offered or used in current NC practice. Every funeral home Duane partners with uses insurance-funded preneed exclusively.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Section 5: Preneed and Medicaid in North Carolina -->
		<section class="mb-16">
			<SectionHeading title="Preneed Insurance and Medicaid in North Carolina" accent />
			<div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					This is one of the most important aspects of preneed planning in North Carolina, and it is frequently misunderstood. If you or a loved one may need Medicaid coverage for long-term care &mdash; nursing home care, assisted living, or in-home care &mdash; understanding how preneed insurance interacts with Medicaid eligibility rules can save your family tens of thousands of dollars.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					To qualify for Medicaid in North Carolina, an individual must have less than <strong>$2,000 in countable assets</strong>. This threshold is extremely low, and it means that most people must "spend down" their savings before Medicaid will begin covering their care. Homes, vehicles, and certain other assets are excluded from this calculation &mdash; and critically, so are <strong>irrevocable preneed funeral trusts</strong>.
				</p>

				<div class="bg-linen rounded-xl p-8 mb-6 border border-border-light">
					<p class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-charcoal-900 mb-2">
						Irrevocable preneed trusts are <span class="text-burgundy-600">exempt</span> from NC Medicaid asset calculations
					</p>
					<p class="text-charcoal-500">This means you can set aside funds for your funeral without jeopardizing your Medicaid eligibility.</p>
				</div>

				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					Here is the key distinction: an <strong>irrevocable</strong> preneed arrangement is one where you permanently give up access to the funds. Once the trust or insurance assignment is made irrevocable, the money can only be used for its intended purpose &mdash; paying for your funeral. Because you no longer have access to or control over those funds, Medicaid does not count them as an asset. A <strong>revocable</strong> preneed arrangement, by contrast, allows you to cancel the plan and reclaim the funds at any time. Because you retain access, Medicaid <em>does</em> count revocable preneed as an asset.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					This distinction creates a powerful planning opportunity. Many families facing the prospect of Medicaid spend-down work with a preneed funeral director and an elder law attorney to convert countable assets into an irrevocable preneed trust. For example, a family might set aside $10,000 or $15,000 for a comprehensive funeral plan, reducing their countable assets and moving closer to Medicaid eligibility &mdash; while ensuring their funeral is fully funded and their wishes are documented.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					It is important to approach this strategically. Medicaid has a five-year "look-back period" during which the state can review financial transactions for evidence of asset transfers designed to artificially reduce wealth. However, purchasing a preneed funeral plan at fair market value is generally not considered a disqualifying transfer, because you are receiving something of equivalent value (a guaranteed funeral) in exchange for your payment. That said, every family's situation is different, and Duane always recommends consulting with an elder law attorney when Medicaid planning is involved.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					North Carolina has similar Medicaid exemptions for irrevocable preneed arrangements, which is relevant for families with ties to North Carolina. For a deeper look at how Medicaid and funeral planning intersect, see our <a href="/learn/medicaid-funeral-planning" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">Medicaid and funeral planning guide</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Section 6: NC Preneed Consumer Rights -->
		<section class="mb-16">
			<SectionHeading title="Your Rights as a Preneed Consumer in North Carolina" accent />
			<div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					North Carolina provides strong consumer protections for preneed purchasers. If you are considering a preneed plan, you should know that the law is firmly on your side. Here are the key rights and protections you have under NC preneed law:
				</p>

				<ul class="space-y-3">
					<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
						<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-teal-600 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
						</svg>
						<span><strong>100% contract transferability</strong> &mdash; You can move your preneed plan to any licensed funeral home in North Carolina at any time, for any reason. You are never locked in to a single provider.</span>
					</li>
					<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
						<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-teal-600 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
						</svg>
						<span><strong>30-day free-look period</strong> &mdash; North Carolina law gives you 30 days from signing to cancel your preneed contract and receive a full refund, no questions asked. After the 30-day free-look period, insurance-funded preneed contracts do not provide a cash refund — however, the contract is fully transferable to another funeral home, and any unused policy value at death is returned to your heirs or assigns.</span>
					</li>
					<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
						<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-teal-600 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
						</svg>
						<span><strong>Mandatory fund protection</strong> &mdash; All preneed funds must be placed in a state-regulated trust or backed by an insurance policy. A preneed seller cannot hold your money outside of these protected structures.</span>
					</li>
					<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
						<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-teal-600 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
						</svg>
						<span><strong>Board of Funeral Service oversight</strong> &mdash; The NC Board of Funeral Service actively regulates preneed activities, investigates consumer complaints, and has the authority to revoke licenses for violations.</span>
					</li>
					<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
						<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-teal-600 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
						</svg>
						<span><strong>Surety bond protection</strong> &mdash; NC law requires preneed licensees (funeral establishments holding preneed contracts) to maintain a surety bond, providing a financial safety net for consumers in the event of misconduct or insolvency. You can verify any preneed licensee’s status through the NC Board of Funeral Service.</span>
					</li>
					<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
						<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-teal-600 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
						</svg>
						<span><strong>2025 NC HB 1003 enhancements</strong> &mdash; Recent legislative changes have further strengthened the preneed framework with religious practice accommodations, trust-to-insurance conversion provisions, and transportation agreement updates.</span>
					</li>
				</ul>

				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					These protections exist because the state recognizes that preneed purchasers are making significant financial commitments based on trust. When you work with a licensed preneed funeral director, you can be confident that your funds are protected and your rights are enforceable. If you ever have concerns about a preneed transaction, the NC Board of Funeral Service is the appropriate authority to contact.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Section 7: How to Choose a Preneed Plan in NC -->
		<section class="mb-16">
			<SectionHeading title="How to Choose a Preneed Plan in NC" accent />
			<div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					Choosing a preneed plan is a significant decision, but it does not have to be overwhelming. The process is straightforward when you work with an experienced, licensed preneed funeral director who takes the time to understand your needs. Here is a practical framework for making the right choice:
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Start with a licensed agent.</strong> This is non-negotiable. Verify that your preneed agent holds a current license through the NC Board of Funeral Service. A licensed agent has met the state's education, bonding, and regulatory requirements. They are accountable to the Board and to you. If someone offers to sell you a preneed plan without a verifiable license, walk away.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Understand your funding option.</strong> In current NC practice, virtually all preneed plans are insurance-funded — this is the standard used by the funeral homes Duane partners with. Insurance-funded preneed provides full coverage from day one (for healthy applicants) and guaranteed growth. If Medicaid planning is a factor, the plan can be structured as irrevocable to qualify for the Medicaid asset exemption. Duane will explain your specific options clearly.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Consider your budget and payment preferences.</strong> Preneed plans can be paid in a single lump sum or over monthly installments spanning 1 to 10 years. A lump-sum payment typically offers the best value because you avoid paying premiums over time. However, monthly payments make preneed accessible to families who cannot commit a large amount upfront. There is no wrong answer &mdash; the best payment plan is the one you can maintain comfortably.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Think about the type of service you want.</strong> Do you envision a traditional burial with a viewing and funeral service? A cremation followed by a celebration of life? A simple, private family gathering? Your preneed plan should reflect your genuine wishes, not what you think is expected. Duane will ask you thoughtful questions about your preferences and help you document every detail. For ideas on non-traditional services, visit our <a href="/celebration-of-life" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">celebration of life planning</a> page.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Ask about Medicaid exemption if it is relevant.</strong> If you or your spouse may need long-term care covered by Medicaid in the future, make sure your preneed plan is structured to qualify for Medicaid exemption. This requires an irrevocable arrangement, and it is best set up before the need for Medicaid arises. Duane has extensive experience with Medicaid-exempt preneed planning and can coordinate with your elder law attorney.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Get everything in writing.</strong> Your preneed contract should clearly document every aspect of your plan: the services selected, the funeral home designated, the funding mechanism, the payment schedule, the cancellation terms, and the transferability provisions. Do not rely on verbal promises. A well-documented contract protects you and your family.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Involve your family.</strong> This is advice that many people overlook, but it is critical. Your preneed plan is ultimately for your family's benefit. Having an open conversation about your wishes &mdash; while you are healthy and clear-headed &mdash; removes the burden of guesswork from your loved ones. Many families find that the conversation, once started, is far less difficult than they imagined. Duane is experienced at facilitating these discussions and can be a neutral, supportive presence. To <a href="/plan-ahead" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">start planning ahead</a>, call <a href={`tel:${PHONE_RAW}`} class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">{PHONE}</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Section 8: Preneed Insurance Carriers Available in NC -->
		<section class="mb-16">
			<SectionHeading title="Preneed Insurance Carriers Available in NC" accent />
			<div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					In North Carolina, the carrier used for your preneed policy is typically determined by the funeral home you select — each funeral home partners with one or more specific carriers. Duane works with the carriers his funeral home partners use. The three primary carriers he works with are listed below; these are the ones you’re most likely to encounter when planning with Duane.
				</p>

				<ul class="space-y-3">
					<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
						<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-teal-600 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
						</svg>
						<span><strong>Great Western Insurance Company (Wellabe)</strong> &mdash; Duane’s primary carrier. Great Western offers competitive whole life preneed products with strong financial ratings and a straightforward claims process. Known for flexibility in plan design and reliable customer service for both families and funeral homes.</span>
					</li>
					<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
						<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-teal-600 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
						</svg>
						<span><strong>Homesteaders Life Company</strong> &mdash; One of the most established preneed carriers in the country, partnering with thousands of funeral homes across the US. Known for competitive pricing, strong financial ratings, and a streamlined claims process.</span>
					</li>
					<li class="flex items-start gap-3 text-charcoal-700">
						<svg class="w-5 h-5 text-teal-600 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
							<path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
						</svg>
						<span><strong>National Guardian Life (NGL)</strong> &mdash; Based in Madison, Wisconsin, NGL offers a range of preneed products and is known for flexibility in plan design and competitive underwriting. A solid choice for families with specific health considerations.</span>
					</li>
				</ul>

				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					Because each funeral home partners with specific carriers, the carrier used for your preneed plan is largely determined by the funeral home you choose to work with. Duane will clearly explain which carrier is used, how the policy is structured, and what protections you have — so you can plan with full confidence. For a no-obligation conversation, <a href="/contact" class="text-teal-600 hover:text-teal-700 underline">contact Duane</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<!-- Section 9: 2025 NC HB 1003 -->
		<section class="mb-16">
			<SectionHeading title="2025 NC HB 1003 — Recent Changes to NC Preneed Law" accent />
			<div class="prose max-w-none text-charcoal-700 space-y-4">
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					In 2025, the North Carolina General Assembly passed House Bill 1003, which introduced several meaningful updates to the state's preneed funeral planning framework. These changes reflect the evolving needs of NC families and modernize certain provisions that had not been updated in years. Here are the key changes:
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Religious practice accommodations.</strong> HB 1003 added provisions that allow preneed contracts to accommodate specific religious practices and requirements. This is significant for families whose faith traditions dictate specific burial timelines, preparation methods, or service formats. Preneed contracts can now explicitly incorporate these requirements, providing legal backing for religious observances within the preneed framework.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Trust-to-insurance conversion provisions.</strong> Perhaps the most practically significant change, HB 1003 allows families with existing trust-funded preneed plans to convert them to insurance-funded plans. This is valuable because insurance-funded plans offer certain advantages &mdash; including full coverage from day one and guaranteed growth &mdash; that trust-funded plans do not provide. Previously, converting between funding mechanisms was more complicated. The new provisions streamline this process and give families more flexibility to adjust their plans as their needs change.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					<strong>Transportation agreement provisions.</strong> The bill also updated regulations around transportation agreements within preneed contracts, clarifying how transportation services between facilities, cemeteries, and other locations can be documented and funded within a preneed plan. This is particularly relevant for families who want services at multiple locations or who live in rural areas where transportation logistics are more complex.
				</p>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					These changes took effect in 2025 and apply to both new and existing preneed contracts in North Carolina. If you have an existing preneed plan and want to understand how these changes might benefit you &mdash; particularly the trust-to-insurance conversion option &mdash; Duane can review your current contract and advise you on your options. For families exploring preneed for the first time, these protections are automatically built into the current contract framework.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

